<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2018/06/06/spring-tips-jpa">Spring Tips: JPA</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/fb22593caf24e4bb4c98d467cdd247e6?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" href="/team/jlong">Josh Long</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2018-06-06 08:01:00.0">June 6, 2018</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="3292" href="/blog/2018/06/06/spring-tips-jpa#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>speaker: <a href="https://twitter.com/starbuxman">Josh Long</a></p>
<p>Hi Spring fans! In this installment we look at the Java Persistence API (JPA) and its most ubiquitous implementation Hibernate. We look at basic Spring support for JPA, Spring Boot’s auto-configuration and supported configuration properties, mapped superclasses, auditing (using Spring Data’s JPA auditing facility) and journaling (using the Hibernate Envers project and Spring Data Envers).</p>
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2E8_0Qxi6Tg" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>
</section>
